module.exports={homepage:{intro:{title:"The Rivalry Issue TMD",subtitle:"A collaboration between The Michigan Daily and The Lantern",paragraph:"Text for the introduction"}},michigan:[{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"desmond-howard-pose"},{type:"title",value:"In 1991, Desmond Howard made the pose heard ‘round the world"},{type:"author",value:"Aria Gerson"},{type:"description",value:"In 1991, Desmond Howard’s iconic Heisman pose after a punt return touchdown"},{type:"date",value:"December 2"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-1.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"Desmond Howard is originally from Cleveland, deep in scarlet and gray territory. Before his final game against Ohio State, he made his friends back home a promise."},{type:"text",value:"“I told my friends from Ohio that if I got in the end zone against Ohio State, I’d do something special for them,” he said after the game."},{type:"text",value:"Then, late in the first half, it happened. Howard fielded a punt, easily dodged through several defenders, ran untouched into the end zone with his hands up and quickly struck the Heisman pose. It was an act of sheer arrogance — though one that was later justified when Howard did indeed win the Heisman Trophy."},{type:"text",value:"Michigan coach Gary Moeller didn’t see the pose at the time — the TV cameras caught it up close — and didn’t even believe it when he was told, going as far as to say, “One of my players would not do that.”"},{type:"text",value:"The pose is now firmly nestled in college football lore and still echoes far beyond Ann Arbor. Plenty of public figures now strike the Heisman pose just as Howard did back then."},{type:"text",value:"Many familiar faces took part in the 1991 Game, including Tyrone Wheatley Sr. and Chris Hutchinson for Michigan — both of whom later had sons play for Michigan — and now-ESPN commentator Kirk Herbstreit, who has called plenty of future iterations of The Game. (Herbstreit was knocked out of the 1991 game on a roughing the passer penalty and would quarterback the Buckeyes to a 13-13 tie the next year.)"},{type:"text",value:"While the ‘90s iterations of The Game were generally exciting and competitive, the 1991 Game was one of the least exciting of the bunch. The outcome was never in doubt, with Michigan (favored coming in at No. 4 to Ohio State’s No. 18) winning, 31-3, its fourth-straight win over the Buckeyes. Howard’s Heisman pose wasn’t the only time Michigan got style points, though. With the game still scoreless and the Wolverines on Ohio State’s 3-yard line, Moeller opted for a fake field goal shovel pass and converted the first down, going on to score a touchdown on the drive. From there, Michigan never looked back."},{type:"text",value:"“I thought it would be closer,” Michigan guard Matt Ellison said at the time. “ … I don’t think they played as well as some of the games we had seen on film.”"},{type:"text",value:"The Wolverines’ win clinched them a spot in the Rose Bowl, which they (as per tradition) lost. Michigan finished the season 10-2 with a Big Ten title, its fourth of five consecutive Big Ten titles."},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes, meanwhile, went to the Hall of Fame Bowl (now the Outback Bowl) in Tampa, Fla., which they lost to Syracuse, finishing 8-4 and third in the Big Ten."},{type:"text",value:"After the game, Howard provided some intrigue by claiming, “I think I’ll definitely be back” at Michigan, but it turned out not to be true. Howard declared for the draft that year and was selected fourth overall by Washington."},{type:"text",value:"Maybe it’s only appropriate that the Heisman pose was among the final moments of Howard’s Michigan career. In 1991, Howard was a consensus All-American, set school records for single-season touchdowns and points and even set a Big Ten record for single-season receiving touchdowns that still stands."},{type:"text",value:"The pose was one indelible moment that perfectly represented all his accolades, his own little piece of history and the one moment — more than the records — that people will always remember."}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"charles-woodson-national"},{type:"title",value:"Michigan reached its modern-day peak with 1997 win"},{type:"author",value:"Theo Mackie"},{type:"description",value:"Heading into the 1997 iteration of The Game, No. 1 Michigan needed a win over No. 4 Ohio State to make the Rose Bowl and keep its National Championship hopes alive. The Wolverines did just that, defeating the Buckeyes, 20-14, en route to their first title in 49 years."},{type:"date",value:"December 1"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-2.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"“It just doesn’t get any better than this.”"},{type:"text",value:"That’s what Charles Woodson told reporters on Nov. 22, 1997, when No. 1 Michigan beat No. 4 Ohio State, 20-14. A month later, though, it did. The Wolverines kicked off 1998 with a 21-16 win over No. 8 Washington State, giving the program its first national title in 49 years."},{type:"text",value:"But it was on that Saturday in late November when Michigan made its greatest mark. In the final year before the BCS National Championship Game was implemented, the Wolverines could not afford to slip up. Undefeated Florida State and Nebraska loomed on their heels in the AP poll."},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes, meanwhile, posed a dangerous threat, even with just one win over Michigan in the prior decade. Their sole loss on the season had come by four points at then-No. 2 Penn State a month prior."},{type:"text",value:"“They say paybacks are a mother and there will be some paybacks Saturday,” Ohio State linebacker Kevin Johnson promised before the game."},{type:"text",value:"On campus, the mood carried an air unrivaled in recent memory, with Michigan on the verge of its first undefeated season since 1971."},{type:"text",value:"In the pregame edition of The Daily, Nicholas Cotsonika wrote, “Anyone who sells their ticket to this game — for no other reason than making a personal profit — should withdraw from school. Now.”"},{type:"text",value:"A day later, those sellers were likely wishing they had heeded Cotsonika’s advice. By the middle of the third quarter, the Wolverines led, 20-0. An Anthony Thomas run opened the scoring, before Charles Woodson’s evaded seven Buckeyes, sending four of them flying to the turf on his famous second-quarter punt return. Andre Weathers’ pick-six finished off the early damage."},{type:"text",value:"“Never before has a Michigan team been this good, this talented, this determined and this well-coached,” John Leroi wrote in the Nov. 24 edition of The Daily. “The Wolverines have suited up for 119 years — and this is the best football team the school has ever fielded.”"},{type:"text",value:"First, though, Michigan had to hold off a final Buckeyes’ push."},{type:"text",value:"Three drives after Weathers’ pick-six, Ohio State quarterback Joe Germaine connected with receiver David Boston for a 56-yard score. The play accounted for over half of Germaine’s 84 passing yards on a day when the combination of the Wolverines’ stifling defense and a cold wintry mix held the Buckeyes to nine completions on 26 pass attempts."},{type:"text",value:"They didn’t fare much better on the ground, either, with 2.9 yards per carry on 41 attempts. It was that ground game, though, that brought Ohio State within six points with 13 minutes remaining after a fumble by Michigan quarterback Brian Griese gave the Buckeyes the ball at the Wolverines’ two-yard line."},{type:"text",value:"From there, Michigan clamped down, holding Ohio State to 20 yards of offense for the rest of the afternoon. And while the Buckeyes trudged to a Sugar Bowl consolation prize after their fifth-straight loss in Ann Arbor, the Wolverines broke a four-year Rose Bowl drought, with national championship aspirations intact."},{type:"text",value:"“When you start coaching, that’s always on the back of your mind,” Michigan coach Lloyd Carr said of national championship aspirations after the game."},{type:"text",value:"Added Griese: “I haven’t achieved my dream yet. I didn’t come back not to win the Rose Bowl. That was my goal from the start.”"},{type:"text",value:"A month later, the Wolverines did just that. Their 1997 season would forever be commemorated in newspaper clippings, photographs and unbreakable memories around the state."},{type:"text",value:"And Woodson’s proclamation still rings true. It would never “get any better than this” for a program that has spent 23 years aiming to rekindle 1997’s magic."}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"failed-two-point-conversion-2013"},{type:"title",value:"Michigan’s 2013 failed two-point conversion changes the course of the rivalry"},{type:"author",value:"Daniel Dash"},{type:"description",value:"A failed two-point conversion attempt in 2013 prevented a struggling Michigan team from stunning the undefeated Buckeyes in Ann Arbor."},{type:"date",value:"November 30, 2013"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-3.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"<b></b>"},{type:"text",value:"One play. Two yards."},{type:"text",value:"In 2013, that’s what decided the Michigan football team’s game against undefeated Ohio State. The unranked Wolverines entered the Saturday after Thanksgiving having lost three of their last four games, but a win over the third-ranked Buckeyes presented an opportunity to erase the embarrassment of a 7-4 record."},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State, on the other hand, was expected to waltz into Ann Arbor and deliver the knockout blow to Michigan’s season. The Buckeyes were vying for a spot in the national title game, and a rivalry win at the Big House was merely supposed to be another box to check."},{type:"text",value:"When Ohio State extended its lead to 35-21 in the late stages of the third quarter, it seemed the game would be exactly that. But Wolverines’ quarterback Devin Gardner refused to go away. The redshirt junior led back-to-back touchdown drives, tying the score at 35 with just five minutes to play. He finished 32-of-45 passing for 451 yards and accounted for five total touchdowns while playing through a foot injury that left him in a boot immediately afterwards."},{type:"text",value:"“He’s a kid,” Michigan coach Brady Hoke said. “He’s learning. I think he’s learning how to be a Michigan quarterback and I think that’s a daily thing. He’s beat up like everybody is, and when he was limping a little bit, I said, ‘I don’t want to see you limp. Every guy out here can limp. We’ve got to go play.’ He did that, and I’m proud of him.”"},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes answered Gardner’s comeback with a touchdown of their own. With 2:20 to play, Michigan had to march down the field to force overtime."},{type:"text",value:"Eleven plays, 84 yards and 1:48 later, the Wolverines got the touchdown they needed. But when Hoke asked for his seniors’ input on the sidelines, they had no interest in kicking a game-tying extra point. Instead, they opted to attempt a game-winning two-point conversion with just 32 seconds remaining."},{type:"text",value:"When Gardner zipped a pass to his right, however, it wasn’t his receiver who came up with the ball. Ohio State cornerback Tyvis Powell stepped in front of the pass and intercepted it, cementing the Buckeyes’ 42-41 victory."},{type:"text",value:"“That’s an instant classic,” Ohio State coach Urban Meyer said."},{type:"text",value:"Those two yards changed the course of the rivalry. Had Michigan converted the two-point attempt, it would’ve marked the Wolverines’ second win over the Buckeyes in three years. The win would’ve stained Meyer’s undefeated two-year run after landing in Columbus. But Powell’s interception gave Ohio State its ninth win in 10 years and maintained the Buckeyes’ dominance over their rival."},{type:"text",value:"Knocking off undefeated Ohio State would’ve given Michigan something to carry into 2014. It could’ve validated Hoke as the right guy for a sputtering program and given him something to sell on the recruiting trail. The two-point conversion could’ve changed the direction of the rivalry, though that may seem like nothing more than wishful thinking on the Wolverines’ behalf when considering the years that followed."},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes have defeated Michigan by double digits in five of six meetings since their narrow 2013 win. They won the national title the next season and have claimed four Big Ten titles since, while the Wolverines have barely sniffed Indianapolis."},{type:"text",value:"Michigan limped into the 2014 season following a 17-point loss to Kansas State in the Buffalo Wild Wings Bowl. The Wolverines dropped three of their first four conference games, including a stunner against Rutgers. It became clear that Hoke’s program was rudderless, and the season culminated in his firing."},{type:"text",value:"His successor, Jim Harbaugh, is set to enter the 2020 iteration of the rivalry under similar circumstances. A struggling Michigan program will aim to knock off a top-five Ohio State team with an undefeated record."},{type:"text",value:"Whether or not this season’s edition of “The Game” comes down to two yards or isn’t even decided by two touchdowns remains to be seen."}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"jim-harbaugh-2016"},{type:"title",value:"Inches changed the tides of Harbaugh’s Michigan reign in 2016 game"},{type:"author",value:"Ethan Sears"},{type:"description",value:"After the 2016 edition of The Game, Michigan coach Jim Harbaugh was upset about a double-overtime spot given to J.T. Barrett that helped decide the outcome. His program hasn’t come close to beating the Buckeyes since."},{type:"date",value:"December 1"},{type:"img",value:"https://therivalrygame.com/mi-cover-img/um-4.jpg"},{type:"text",value:"Whenever and however the Jim Harbaugh era ends at Michigan, it will be looked back upon as the biggest what-if of his tenure. J.T. Barrett falling into tight end A.J. Alexander, the ball outstretched in his hands. Eleven Michigan players waving their arms to signal he didn’t cross the line; 11 Ohio State players pointing forwards to signal first down."},{type:"text",value:"And just minutes later, Buckeyes running back Curtis Samuel running into the end zone untouched to give Ohio State a 30-27, double-overtime win in the most memorable edition of The Game this decade."},{type:"text",value:"“I am bitterly disappointed with the officiating today,” Michigan coach Jim Harbaugh said. “That spot.”"},{type:"text",value:"He held his hands apart to show how short he thought Barrett was. He asked reporters what they thought. He got fined $10,000 by the Big Ten the following Monday for comments on the officiating that went on to include gripes about pass interference calls and an unsportsmanlike conduct penalty incurred after he threw his play card and slammed his headset in the third quarter."},{type:"text",value:"“We won the game,” Ohio State coach Urban Meyer said, and indeed, history has no sympathy for Harbaugh’s complaints."},{type:"text",value:"The 2016 team was undoubtedly Harbaugh’s best thus far at Michigan, coming into The Game ranked third in the country and in control of its own destiny for a College Football Playoff spot. Nonetheless, it couldn’t take down Ohio State, which was ranked second and went on to make the Playoff."},{type:"text",value:"Despite the controversy over the spot, the Wolverines had plenty of opportunities to avoid overtime altogether. Nursing a shoulder injury, quarterback Wilton Speight committed two key turnovers — a second-quarter pick six and a third-quarter fumble on Ohio State’s one-yard line. Michigan led by as much as 17-7, with Don Brown’s defense holding the Buckeyes to 330 total yards, but it wasn’t enough."},{type:"text",value:"A second Speight interception allowed Ohio State to cut the lead to three and Barrett led the Buckeyes to a game-tying drive at the end of regulation, with Tyler Durbin kicking a 23-yard field goal."},{type:"text",value:"In the three editions of The Game since, the Wolverines have never come as close to winning. And in the last two years, their defense hasn’t been close to the same level — in 2018 and 2019, Ohio State’s offensive yardage totals were 567 and 577, respectively."},{type:"text",value:"At the time, it seemed to represent a new era for the rivalry, and maybe a new 10-year war between Harbaugh and Meyer. Michigan had lost, but proven it could play on equal footing with its greatest rival in their home stadium."},{type:"text",value:"With the glint of perspective, even that most optimistic of takeaways proved completely wrong. Meyer retired after once again keeping Michigan from a College Football Playoff berth in the Horseshoe in 2018. Harbaugh finds himself on the hot seat heading into this year’s game. The Wolverines haven’t been competitive with Ohio State since then, and few expect them to be in 2020."},{type:"text",value:"If that spot is different, maybe everything else is, too. Maybe Michigan wins the Big Ten, makes the College Football Playoff, keeps recruiting at a top-five level nationally and a newly-renewed 10-year war comes to fruition. Maybe this rivalry is competitive, instead of a yearly funeral procession to the Wolverines’ season."},{type:"text",value:"But maybes will do no solace to Harbaugh, nor to Michigan’s program."}]}],lantern:[{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"ohio-states-success"},{type:"title",value:"Ohio State’s success with and without breakout running backs"},{type:"author",value:"Keaton Maisano"},{type:"description",value:"Ohio State has dominated Michigan over the past decade, and that dominance can largely be linked to the Buckeyes’ success on the ground."},{type:"date",value:"December 1"},{type:"img",value:"https://www.thelantern.com/files/2019/11/edit-8059.jpg"},{type:"caption",value:"Ohio State then-junior running back J.K. Dobbins (2) runs the ball down the field to score a touchdown during the second half of the game against Michigan at Michigan Stadium Nov. 30. Ohio State won 56-27. Credit: Amal Saeed | Lantern File Photo"},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State has dominated Michigan over the past decade, and that dominance can largely be linked to the Buckeyes’ success on the ground."},{type:"text",value:"Over the last 10 meetings between the rivals, Ohio State running backs have rushed for more than 100 yards on seven occasions. In many of these cases, the Buckeyes employed elite talent at the running back position with six of the last seven feature backs entering The Game with more than 1,000 yards rushing on the season."},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State running backs failed to eclipse 1,000 rushing yards prior to the Michigan game from 2010-12. Over the three year stretch, the Buckeyes went 2-1 against the Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"In the two victories, Ohio State’s No. 1 running back dashed for 175 yards in 2010 and 146 yards in 2012."},{type:"text",value:"In the lone loss in 2011, then-redshirt senior running back Dan Herron was held to 37 yards and a touchdown on 15 carries. Then-freshman quarterback Braxton Miller would add 100 yards and a touchdown on the ground, but the Buckeyes would fall 40-34."},{type:"text",value:"In his second season as the feature back, then-senior Carlos Hyde led the shift from a quarterback-centric running game by becoming the first Buckeye running back in the decade to enter The Game with more than 1,000 yards on the season."},{type:"text",value:"Hyde also became the first Ohio State running back to rush for more than 200 yards in The Game — tallying the highest total in the history of the rivalry with 226 yards in the thrilling 42-41 win over the Wolverines in 2013."},{type:"text",value:"Over the next four seasons, Buckeye running backs followed Hyde’s lead, each entering The Game with more than 1,000 yards. In their rivalry matchups, three of the four Ohio State running backs were able to eclipse 100 yards — including a 214-yard, two-touchdown performance from then-junior Ezekiel Elliott in 2015."},{type:"text",value:"Elliott had one of the more productive runs as the No. 1 back in The Game. In two games, Elliott rushed for 335 yards and four touchdowns and earned two pairs of gold pants."},{type:"text",value:"In 2016, No. 2 Ohio State played host to No. 3 Michigan. Then-freshman running back Mike Weber entered the game as Ohio State’s leading rusher with 1,046 yards, but the Michigan native was held mostly in check — finishing the game with 26 rushing yards and a touchdown on 11 carries."},{type:"text",value:"Like previous seasons, Ohio State leaned on the quarterback position for an added element to the rushing attack. Then-redshirt junior quarterback J.T. Barrett would obtain 125 yards and a touchdown on 30 carries."},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State’s 30-27 win in overtime would be stamped off a touchdown run from then-junior running back Curtis Samuel, who finished the game with 54 rushing yards."},{type:"text",value:"Running back J.K. Dobbins’ arrival in 2017 marked the transition to the next running back at Ohio State."},{type:"text",value:"His freshman campaign included 1,403 rushing yards and a performance against Michigan in which he eclipsed 100 yards and found the end zone."},{type:"text",value:"The 2018 season saw an unusual shift for the Buckeyes. Leaning on a passing attack led by then-redshirt sophomore Dwayne Haskins, Ohio State entered the Michigan game without a running back eclipsing 1,000 yards for the first time since 2012."},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes would use 396 passing yards from Haskins to down Michigan 62-39. Dobbins would finish with 46 yards on 12 carries while Weber would lead the team with 96 yards on 13 carries."},{type:"text",value:"Dobbins would break through the following year with a record-setting season."},{type:"text",value:"The then-junior running back would amass 1,446 yards and 15 touchdowns entering the Michigan game, and he would add 211 yards and four touchdowns against the Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"Dobbins would go on to break the Ohio State single-season rushing record — previously held by Eddie George. He would finish the season with 2,003 rushing yards and 21 touchdowns on the ground."},{type:"text",value:"In terms of total yards, Hyde produced the most in his appearances in the rivalry with 372 while Dobbins was able to find the end zone the most — finishing with five touchdowns in his three appearances. Elliott led the way in yards per attempt, gathering an average of 7.13 yards on each carry in his two performances."},{type:"text",value:"Although 2018 served as an outlier, the path to success against Michigan the past decade has been on the ground — not through the air."}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"the-longest-win-streaks"},{type:"title",value:"The longest winning streaks in the history of The Game"},{type:"author",value:"Jack Emerson"},{type:"description",value:"As the Buckeyes look to tie the series-longest nine-game winning streak Dec. 12, here’s an in-depth look back at some of the longest winning streaks in the rivalry."},{type:"date",value:"December 1"},{type:"img",value:"https://www.thelantern.com/files/2019/11/edit-7037.jpg"},{type:"caption",value:"Ohio State then-sophomore wide receiver Chris Olave (17) celebrates after scoring a touchdown during the first half of the game against Michigan at Michigan Stadium Nov. 30. Ohio State won 56-27. Credit: Amal Saeed | Lantern File Photo"},{type:"text",value:"Since 2012, Ohio State has been in the midst of one of the longest winning streaks in the history of its illustrious rivalry with Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"As the Buckeyes look to tie the series-longest nine-game winning streak Dec. 12, here’s an in-depth look back at some of the longest winning streaks in the rivalry."},{type:"<b>1901-09",value:"Michigan wins nine straight</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b></b>"},{type:"text",value:"From Ohio State and Michigan’s first meeting in 1897 to 1918, the Buckeyes failed to beat their rival to the north. The Wolverines amassed a 12-0-2 record against the Buckeyes in that span — including a rivalry-best nine straight wins from 1901-09."},{type:"text",value:"The Wolverines kick-started the run with a 21-0 win over the Buckeyes in 1901."},{type:"text",value:"A year later, Michigan won by the greatest margin of victory in the rivalry’s history with a dominating 86-0 victory over Ohio State in Ann Arbor. It is believed that on the train back to Columbus following Ohio State’s catastrophic defeat, then-freshman defensive end and glee club member Fred Cornell wrote the lyrics to “Carmen Ohio” — marking the beginning of a classic Ohio State tradition."},{type:"text",value:"The Wolverines continued their dominance over the early stages of the rivalry, especially on the defensive end, as the Buckeyes failed to score more than six points in each matchup during the nine-year run. Ohio State was shut out in six of the nine losses."},{type:"text",value:"Michigan outscored Ohio State 285-18 during the record winning streak."},{type:"<b>2012-19",value:"Ohio State wins eight straight</b>"},{type:"text",value:"Over the eight-year stretch, each team has transitioned to a new head coach, but the results have stayed the same, with Ohio State ahead and Michigan trailing behind."},{type:"text",value:"Although Brady Hoke was able to begin his tenure with a win over Ohio State in 2011, he failed to beat the Buckeyes in each of his next three attempts. 2012 not only marked the beginning of the end for Hoke, but it began the seven-year dominance of Urban Meyer in the rivalry."},{type:"text",value:"Meyer would end all seven of his regular seasons at Ohio State with a win over Michigan. The biggest matchup under his watch would occur in 2016 when he led the No. 2 Buckeyes over No. 3 Michigan in an overtime thriller to earn a spot in the College Football Playoff."},{type:"text",value:"Even with the hiring of Jim Harbaugh in December of 2014, the Buckeyes continued to dominate the series."},{type:"text",value:"Meyer’s departure at the end of the 2018 season appeared to be an opportunity for Harbaugh to earn his first victory over the Buckeyes, but first-year head coach Ryan Day was able to take his No. 1 Ohio State team into Michigan Stadium and emphatically extend the streak to eight games with a 56-27 win."},{type:"<b>2004-10*",value:"Ohio State wins seven* straight </b>"},{type:"text",value:"In 2001, the Buckeyes hired head coach Jim Tressel, who brought back the emphasis toward the rivalry between the two programs."},{type:"text",value:"Tressel saw his greatest success from 2004-10, winning seven straight games against Ohio State’s heated rival."},{type:"text",value:"The streak began when the Buckeyes pulled off a major upset at home against the No. 7 Wolverines, winning 37-21. Then-redshirt junior quarterback Troy Smith led Ohio State, throwing for 241 yards and 2 touchdowns while adding 145 yards and a touchdown on the ground."},{type:"text",value:"After earning another win in 2005, the Buckeyes entered the 2006 matchup as the No. 1 team in the country. Michigan entered the game as No. 2, creating an all-time great atmosphere in the rivalry."},{type:"text",value:"The game lived up to the hype — being dubbed “The Game of the Century” — Tressel earned his third straight win against the Wolverines and Smith added to his Heisman Trophy resume with an all-time performance."},{type:"text",value:"Tressel would not lose to Michigan in his Ohio State career again prior to his abrupt departure in 2010, however the 2010 win was vacated by the NCAA."}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"ohio-state-dominance"},{type:"title",value:"Ohio State dominance transcends the scoreboard"},{type:"author",value:"Keaton Maisano and Jack Emerson"},{type:"description",value:"Ohio State has had success against Michigan throughout the past decade and the dominance has transitioned to the NFL draft."},{type:"date",value:"December 1st"},{type:"img",value:"https://www.thelantern.com/files/2019/11/edit-7982.jpg"},{type:"caption",value:"Ohio State then-junior defensive end Chase Young (2) attempts to evade Michigan graduate offensive lineman Jon Runyan (75) during the second half of the game at Michigan Stadium Nov. 30. Ohio State won 56-27. Credit: Amal Saeed | Lantern File Photo"},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State has dominated Michigan over the past decade and the dominance has been evident in the early picks in the NFL drafts."},{type:"text",value:"Since 2016, Ohio State has had six players drafted in the top-five picks of the NFL draft — the most of any program in that time span. The Wolverines, on the other hand, have not had a top-five selection since 2008 when offensive tackle Jake Long was taken first overall."},{type:"text",value:"Ohio State’s highly touted NFL prospects left their mark on the rivalry’s history books with some great performances in the yearly matchup."},{type:"text",value:"<b>2016 — No. 3: Joey Bosa (11 tackles, 4.5 tackles for loss, 3.5 sacks, 1 interception, 1 forced fumble)*</b>"},{type:"text",value:"The older Bosa brother never wasted an opportunity to have an impact game against the Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"In three career games against the Wolverines, Bosa recorded at least one tackle, 0.5 tackles for loss and 0.5 sacks in each of his appearances in The Game."},{type:"text",value:"Bosa’s best performance came in his final regular season game as a Buckeye in 2015 with Bosa collecting three tackles, one tackle for loss, a sack, an interception and a forced fumble in Ohio State’s 42-13 win over Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"In the 2016 NFL draft, Bosa became the first Buckeye drafted in the top five since linebacker A.J. Hawk was selected No. 5 by the Packers in 2006. Bosa was selected No. 3 overall by the then-San Diego Chargers."},{type:"text",value:"<b>2016 — No. 4: Ezekiel Elliott (47 carries, 335 rushing yards, 4 touchdowns)*</b>"},{type:"text",value:"The Dallas Cowboys used the pick after Bosa on another Buckeye, this time on the offensive side of the ball."},{type:"text",value:"Running back Ezekiel Elliott played a crucial role in Ohio State’s victories over Michigan in 2014 and 2015."},{type:"text",value:"Elliott pieced together a 121-yard performance in his rivalry debut in 2014, adding two touchdowns through the ground."},{type:"text",value:"A year later, Elliott exploded for 214 yards and two touchdowns against the Wolverines, leading the Buckeyes to their fourth-straight victory over their rival."},{type:"text",value:"Elliott became the first running back picked in the top five since former Alabama running back Trent Richardson was selected No. 3 by the Cleveland Browns in 2012."},{type:"text",value:"<b>2018 — No. 4: Denzel Ward (11 tackles, 3 pass deflections)*</b>"},{type:"text",value:"In two appearances in The Game, Ward kept up his lockdown distinction in his battles with the Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"In his rivalry debut in 2016, Ward collected three tackles and broke up a pass."},{type:"text",value:"In his next bout with the Wolverines, Ward had a top-tier performance in the backend of the Ohio State defense. Ward finished with a team-high eight tackles and two pass breakups."},{type:"text",value:"Ward was selected by the Cleveland Browns with the No. 4 pick in the 2018 draft."},{type:"text",value:"<b>2019 — No. 2: Nick Bosa (7 tackles, 2 sacks)*</b>"},{type:"text",value:"A few years after Joey Bosa’s reign of terror on the Ohio State defensive line, his younger brother, Nick, appeared to be another threat to Michigan’s offense."},{type:"text",value:"Nick Bosa recorded a sack in his first career bout with the Wolverines in 2016 along with two tackles."},{type:"text",value:"In 2017, the younger Bosa brother improved on his performance from a year prior, adding five tackles alongside a sack."},{type:"text",value:"In the 2019 NFL draft, Nick Bosa was selected one pick ahead of his older brother, joining his brother professionally in California. Bosa joined the talented defensive line corps of the San Francisco 49ers."},{type:"text",value:"<b>2020 — No. 2: Chase Young (2 tackles, 1 tackle for loss, 1 pass deflection)*</b>"},{type:"text",value:"Then-junior defensive end Chase Young had high expectations heading into his final matchup against Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"Although he did not tally a tackle — let alone a sack — Young’s production was largely diminished by the double teams he received throughout the game."},{type:"text",value:"As a team, the Buckeyes recorded two sacks to go along with eight tackles for loss."},{type:"text",value:"In his two games played, Young would tally two tackles, a tackle for loss and a pass deflection against Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"Young was taken No. 2 overall by the Washington Football Team in the 2020 NFL draft."},{type:"text",value:"<b>2020 — No. 3: Jeff Okudah (4 tackles, 2 pass deflections)*</b>"},{type:"text",value:"Two years after Ward left for the NFL, then-junior Jeff Okudah was the next highly-touted corner back to occupy Ohio State’s secondary."},{type:"text",value:"In two career games against the Wolverines, Okudah recorded four tackles and was in on a pair of pass deflections. In 2019, Okudah would be part of a secondary that struggled heavily in the first half — allowing 250 passing yards in the first half."},{type:"text",value:"However, Okudah and the secondary would stifle Michigan’s passing attack in the second half and hold the Wolverines to only 65 passing yards."},{type:"text",value:"Okudah was drafted by the Detroit Lions with the No. 3 overall pick in the 2020 NFL draft."},{type:"text",value:"<b>*Career Stats vs. Michigan</b>"}]},{type:"article",value:[{type:"slug",value:"ohio-passing-and-receiving"},{type:"title",value:"Ohio State’s top passing and receiving games in The Game’s history"},{type:"author",value:"Keaton Maisano and Jack Emerson"},{type:"description",value:"A look at Ohio State’s top individual passing and receiving games against Michigan."},{type:"date",value:"December 1st"},{type:"img",value:"https://www.thelantern.com/files/2018/11/IMG_0379-1a1zj13.jpg"},{type:"caption",value:"Ohio State then-redshirt sophomore quarterback Dwayne Haskins (7) looks to pass the ball during the second half of the game against Michigan on Nov. 24. Ohio State won 62-39. credit: Amal Saeed | Lantern File Photo"},{type:"text",value:"Throughout the history of The Game, Ohio State and Michigan have largely slugged it out in the trenches and on the ground, but there have been plenty of iconic passing and receiving displays in the rivalry."},{type:"<b>Passing",value:"</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>No. 1: Dwayne Haskins (2018) — 396 yards, 6 TDs, 0 INTs, 20/31</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>Ohio State won 62-39</b>"},{type:"text",value:"The 2018 iteration of The Game brought a top-ranked Michigan defense to Ohio Stadium to square off with Ohio State’s potent passing attack."},{type:"text",value:"In what was expected to be Michigan head coach Jim Harbaugh’s first career win against Ohio State, then-redshirt sophomore quarterback Dwayne Haskins spoiled his day with an all-time great performance."},{type:"text",value:"Haskins threw for nearly 400 yards and added six touchdowns while helping the Buckeyes to their highest scoring total in the rivalry’s history — 62 points."},{type:"text",value:"Haskins’ 396 yards and six touchdown passes both are Ohio State records in their yearly matchup with the Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"The New Jersey native would go on to finish the season with Big Ten records in both yards and touchdowns with 4,831 and 50, respectively."},{type:"text",value:"<b>No. 2: Joe Germaine (1998) — 330 yards, 3 TDs, 0 INTs, 16/28</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>Ohio State won 31-16</b>"},{type:"text",value:"Then-senior quarterback Joe Germaine entered the 1998 game with a wealth of receiving talent around him and tremendous amount of pressure after failing to produce a win in his first two career starts against Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"Germaine would not succumb to the pressure and had one of the best performances in his Buckeye career against the then-No 11 Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"The Colorado native outdueled Michigan quarterback Tom Brady, throwing for a then-Ohio State rivalry record 330 yards and three touchdowns in the 31-16 triumph over the Wolverines in Columbus."},{type:"text",value:"Germaine’s efforts helped former Buckeye coach John Cooper earn his second, and final, career win against the Wolverines."},{type:"text",value:"Germaine finished his senior season with 3,330 yards and 25 touchdowns while leading the Buckeyes to a Sugar Bowl victory."},{type:"text",value:"<b>No. 3: Troy Smith (2006) — 316 yards, 4 TDs, 1 INT, 29/41</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>Ohio State won 42-39 </b>"},{type:"text",value:"“The Game of the Century” largely landed on the shoulders of Ohio State’s Heisman-candidate and then-redshirt senior quarterback Troy Smith."},{type:"text",value:"Smith stepped up in a big way in the matchup between the two top-ranked teams in the country, throwing for more than 300 yards and connecting on four touchdown passes while completing just more than 70 percent of his passes."},{type:"text",value:"The 42-39 win allowed the Buckeyes to hold the top spot in the country and earn an opportunity to play in the BCS National Championship game. Ohio State would not prevail in the title game, falling to Florida 41-14."},{type:"text",value:"Smith would go on to earn the highest individual honor in college football — the Heisman Trophy — with a stat line of 2,542 passing yards and 30 touchdowns."},{type:"<b>Receiving",value:"</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>No. 1 David Boston (1998) — 10 catches, 217 yards, 2 TDs</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>Ohio State won 31-16</b>"},{type:"text",value:"Then-junior wide receiver David Boston had a special year in 1998, but possibly the highlight of his season came in a late November matchup with Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"Boston would put together a performance better than any Ohio State wide receiver before him when playing Michigan, and his 217 receiving yards have yet to be topped. The Texas native hauled in 10 catches and two touchdowns in his climb above the 200-yard mark."},{type:"text",value:"His performance is still No. 4 in most receiving yards by an Ohio State receiver in a single game, and Boston sits at No. 2 for most receiving yards in an Ohio State career."},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes would win the game 31-16 and Boston would finish the season with a school-record 1,435 receiving yards and 13 touchdowns."},{type:"text",value:"Boston would be selected No. 8 overall by the Arizona Cardinals in the 1999 NFL draft."},{type:"text",value:"<b>No. 2 Paris Campbell (2018) — 6 catches, 192 yards, 2 TDs</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>Ohio State won 62-39</b>"},{type:"text",value:"The Wolverines had no answer for then-senior wide receiver Paris Campbell’s speed in 2018."},{type:"text",value:"Campbell would save his best performance for his last game at Ohio Stadium when the Buckeyes were able to down Michigan 62-39."},{type:"text",value:"Not only would the Ohio native tally a career-high 192 receiving yards, but he would dash for the longest play of his career when he took a touch pass 78 yards to the endzone."},{type:"text",value:"Campbell would finish the game with a pair of touchdowns. He would finish his senior season with 1,063 receiving yards to go along with 12 touchdowns."},{type:"text",value:"The second-round selection in the 2019 NFL draft is just one of five players to eclipse the 1,000-yard receiving mark in a single season at Ohio State."},{type:"text",value:"<b>No. 3 Michael Jenkins (2003)* — 9 catches, 132 yards, 0 TD</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>*Santonio Holmes (2003) — 8 catches, 121 yards, 2 TDs</b>"},{type:"text",value:"<b>Ohio State lost 35-21</b>"},{type:"text",value:"The Buckeyes would turn to the air in an attempt to beat the Wolverines in 2003, and although two Ohio State receivers were able to put on impressive performances, it was not enough to prevent former head coach Jim Tressel from dropping his first — and only — game to Michigan."},{type:"text",value:"Then-junior wide receiver Michael Jenkins would provide the Buckeyes with a game-high 132 receiving yards. The national champion would also bring in nine catches but fail to see any result in six points."},{type:"text",value:"Jenkins was not alone in his ability to punish the Wolverine secondary, as then-redshirt freshman wide receiver Santonio Holmes added another eight catches for 121 yards."},{type:"text",value:"Unlike Jenkins, Holmes was able to turn two of his catches into touchdowns."},{type:"text",value:"The game still stands as the only instance in which two Ohio State teammates each topped 100 receiving yards against Michigan."}]}]};
